COMMENTS 

e would like to thank our colleagues W(Neff et al., this issue) for clarifying sev­eral points raised by the compositional study reported by Blomster, Neff, and Glascock (2005) that were not clear until now. We also appre­ciate this opportunity to respond to Neff et al.'s defense of Blomster et al. Some response is clearly needed, because Neff et al. do not appear to under­stand why the peer-reviewed Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences (PNAS) articles by Stoltman et al. (2005) and Flannery et al. (2005) were written. We agree with Neff et al. that it is the creation of reliable data that is important, especially data from which we can build reliable inferences about the past. In the commentary that follows we will point out crucial weaknesses in the pottery data on which Blomster et al. propose to build inferences about the past, weaknesses that would appear to make it difficult, if not impossible, to make bridg­ing arguments that link these data with the kinds of inferences about patterns of regional and inter­regional exchange during the Mesoamerican Early Formative described by Blomster et al. We also agree with Neff et al. and Blomster et al. regarding the need to move away from the outmoded and unproductive debate between two models that have far too long dominated discussion of the origins and development of complexity during the Early For­mative. We are glad to see that Neff et al. now appear to agree with us that one of these, the so­called mother culture model, is not "analytically useful," a conclusion reached by most Mesoamer­ican scholars almost two decades ago (Sharer and Grove 1989). The response by Neff et al. is mostly devoted to the defense of instrumental neutron activation analysis (INAA) studies of pottery and criticism of the petrographic analysis reported by Stoltman et al. (2005). This issue involves the way specific high-tech analytical methods are used in ceramic analysis to determine production sources. The sug­gestions that emerge from this discussion can per­haps serve as a guide for future researchers. Neff et al. devote relatively little space to the larger and 
more important issues raised by Blomster et al.'s cultural-historical interpretation of their analyses and discussed by Flannery et al. (2005), namely, the restatement of fundamental propositions based on the mother culture model and the appropriate­ness of the use of their INAA analyses of sherds for deriving conclusions, a topic that falls more in the realm of archaeological inference. All of us, whatever our specialty, agree that Neff et al. mis­understand or misrepresent critical portions of the two PNAS articles (Stoltman et al. 2005 and Flan­nery et al. 2005) and, interestingly enough, also misrepresent what Blomster et al. say in at least two crucial areas. 
Ceramic Sourcing 
We follow the commonsense approach advocated by Rice (1987:317-329; see also Hench 1971) in her work on ceramic characterization. Of course, all ceramic analyses should begin with sherds or whole vessels from well-documented contexts. It is always "best to begin with the simplest tech­niques or properties for characterization and work up to more complex and costly ones. In other words, there should be constant interaction between suc­cessive levels of analysis and selection of samples for additional study, always using earlier findings as guidelines for later procedures" (Rice 1987:323-324, 326). When analyzing sherd sam­ples, all that is needed to begin are a lOx hand lens and pliers to create freshly broken cross sections. If not already classified, the sherd samples should be grouped by types, vessel shapes, surface treat­ments, colors, decoration, or other meaningful vari­ables that covary over a specified region during a specified time period. Of course, archaeologists who classify sherds become so familiar with the intimate details of their local pottery types that for­eign wares are typically recognizable by inspection. It was this intimate familiarity with Woodland pot­tery (disparaged by Neff et al.) that made Stoltman and Mainfort (2002) skeptical of Neff's and Glas­cock's claim that "all" pottery at the Pinson Mounds site was locally made. 
Mineralogical analysis is next on Rice's list, preferably petrography, comparing the constituents of sherds to the local bedrock geology of the local site or region. For example, in the Mexican high­lands the andesite porphyry temper in the pottery type called Tortuga Polished relates it to the andesite hill behind Tlapacoya, and the gneiss tem­per in the type called Leandro Gray relates it to the Precambrian gneiss piedmont near San Jose Mogote (Stoltman et al. 2005). This type of min-
