eralogical evidence refutes Blomster et al.'s claims that "all" carved gray ware originated at San Lorenzo and that highland valleys did not exchange pottery with each other. 
Finally, save the costly bulk chemical compo­sition analysis (e.g., INAA) for last, when you know which questions to ask of which sherds. If, for example, you have groups of virtually untempered fine wares that do not contribute sufficient miner­alogical detail through petrographic characteriza­tion, see whether they can be distinguished by INAA. This is why Stoltman and Mainfort (2002), as well as Rice ( 1987), recommend using a com­bination of petrography and INAA. Neff et al. now seem to welcome the use of such a combination; however, there is little evidence that Blomster et al. felt this way when they were irradiating their 944 Formative sherd samples. At that time they appeared confident that they could bypass all lower­tech procedures; in parts of table 2 of their Science Web site supporting data, we are not even given the basic type identifications of some sherds. 
Neutron activation analysis has long-understood limitations (Rice 1987:413-426), as even Neff et al. acknowledge, and we are struck by how candid its Old World practitioners are about them. To begin with, those scholars stress that INAA does not, in fact, reveal "sources" of pottery. INAA only cre­ates "chemical composition groups," that is, clus­ters of sherds whose parts per million/billion of various elements are similar. Chemical composi­tion can only be most directly and reliabl y com­pared to geological resources (i.e., it is a geochemical problem, method, and set of data); the question of where a pot was made is a cultural question and requires many intervening assump­tions between geochemical composition and human behavior (see also Adan-Bayewitz and Wieder 1992:191; Day et al. 1999:1026). Thus, whenever Blomster et al. or Neff et al. say that INAA has revealed that sherd X is an import from site Y, they exceed the limits of the technique. 
Neff and Glascock should be aware of this, because they earlier reported a "troubling similar­ity" in chemical composition between one Valley of Oaxaca composition group and the largest San Lorenzo composition group (2002: 10). In other words, by sheer coincidence, ceramics made from mineralogically different clays and tempers can have similar parts per million compositions of var­ious chemical elements. Compounding this prob­lem is the fact that INAA cannot determine whether the source of a given element comes from the clay, the temper, the substances cooked or stored in the pot, or the soil in which the sherds lay buried. As it happens, petrography can separate the Oaxaca and San Lorenzo sherds in question by identifying the temper minerals (Stoltman et al. 2005: figure2). 

In an overview of Bronze Age pottery sourcing, Knapp and Cherry wonder why petrography is not used more often, in light of geochemical analysis' "failure to relate analytical results to the natural variation inherent in both raw material s and pro­duction techniques" ( 1994: 19). They specifically single out Stoltman's ( 1991) "point counting" pro­cedure, which adds a quantitative dimension to pet­rography. It might be ill uminating to appl y this procedure to all the Mesoamerican data sets to which only INAA has been applied in the past. 
In considering the relationship between INAA and petrography, the similarity in the results between the Pinson Mounds and Mesoamerican Formative pottery analyses is striking and merits further discussion. In each case, INAA analyses of several hundred sherds led the investigators to con­clude thatall pottery (excluding unassigned sherds) was locally produced (Blomster et al. 2005; Main­fort et al. 1997). Subsequent petrographic anal yses contradicted these conclusions, with profound implications for the relative rel iability of the two techniques to address issues of pottery production and exchange. 
In referring to Stoltman and Mainfort's Pinson study, in which 39 sherds were analyzed by both INAA and petrography, Neff et al. badly misrep­resent the petrographic findings. For exampl e, they mention only the texture differences observed in three sand-tempered specimens out of the 39, call­ing them "feeble." In actuality, a minimum of five other vessels were found to be characterized by exotic tempers such as grog, bone, quartzite, and limestone and were also identified as probable exotics (Stol tman and Mainfort 2002: 10). Neff et al. dismiss the findings of the Formative petro­graphic study on the grounds that the range of com­positional variation of both San Lorenzo and Oaxaca pottery had not been established. This, of course, is a red herring. The concl usion that spe­cific pottery recovered at San Lorenzo was most likely imported from Oaxaca is based on these 
